```
i=1 → nums[1]=2 → 2 != 3? YES ← keep
  nums[0] = 2   (write 2 at position k=0)
  k = 1
  nums = [2, 2, 2, 3]
```
```
i=2 → nums[2]=2 → 2 != 3? YES ← keep
  nums[1] = 2   (write 2 at position k=1)
  k = 2
  nums = [2, 2, 2, 3]
```
```
i=3 → nums[3]=3 → 3 != 3? NO  ← skip
  k stays at 2
  nums = [2, 2, 2, 3]
```
```
return k = 2 ✅

First 2 elements: [2, 2]  ← these are the valid ones
```

